1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:08,573
Namo tassa bhagavato harahato samma sambodassam

2
00:00:09,076 --> 00:00:32,158
Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Namo tassa bhagavato arahato samma sambuddhasa Homage to the Buddha, the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one.

3
00:00:34,901 --> 00:00:36,281
So I thought I'd...

4
00:00:38,049 --> 00:00:39,271
Look at the word buddha.

5
00:00:43,537 --> 00:00:54,174
Since this weekend we celebrate his birth, enlightenment and parinibbana, total nibbana.

6
00:00:54,195 --> 00:00:57,460
We don't say his death, although he died.

7
00:01:01,024 --> 00:01:03,027
It's celebrated every...

8
00:01:04,072 --> 00:01:26,873
properly at the full moon of May which is towards the end of the dry season so you're looking to the rains it's like spring really so that's the traditional time other forms of Buddhism celebrate it at other times of the year so

9
00:01:28,944 --> 00:01:33,632
So the first thing is that there are three types of Buddhas.

10
00:01:34,013 --> 00:01:36,075
There's the self-enlightened Buddha.

11
00:01:37,298 --> 00:01:40,983
There's what we call the private Buddha.

12
00:01:42,004 --> 00:01:47,233
And there's the Buddha who was a follower of a Buddha.

13
00:01:48,594 --> 00:01:53,923
So if we look at the first one, the Sambuddho, we have nine Buddhas.

14
00:01:56,536 --> 00:02:18,983
qualities and we chant them in the morning iti piso bhagava arahant sammasambuddho vidyacarana sampanno sugato lokavidu anuttaro purisadam sarati satta deva manusanan buddho bhagavati

15
00:02:18,962 --> 00:02:25,133
The first one is Arahant, and that refers to the fact that all his defilements have been destroyed.

16
00:02:25,713 --> 00:02:36,229
So that's not only the moral stuff, killing and all that, it's also depression, anxiety, all the secondary stuff about guilt and shame.

17
00:02:36,250 --> 00:02:37,872
So the heart's completely purified.

18
00:02:39,034 --> 00:02:44,143
So the word Arahant refers to the end of all defilements.

19
00:02:45,945 --> 00:02:51,598
Sammasambuddho refers to the fact that he's self-enlightened.

20
00:02:52,378 --> 00:03:01,137
And what that means is that there was nobody around at that time who knew where the path was.

21
00:03:02,348 --> 00:03:11,377
So he worked with various teachers, he did various mortifications, all that was offered at the time, but they didn't seem to get him anywhere.

22
00:03:11,757 --> 00:03:17,461
And it was a memory from childhood, which, as it were, set him on the path.

23
00:03:17,943 --> 00:03:25,250
So it's because of that, because of that memory, because he goes back to his own life, that we say he's self-enlightened.

24
00:03:28,712 --> 00:03:31,596
And that's what that Sammasambuddho refers to.

25
00:03:35,777 --> 00:03:44,663
Vidya-carana-sampanno means, the vidya means knowledge, wisdom, and the vidya-carana means his conduct.

26
00:03:45,504 --> 00:03:50,800
So it wasn't a case of, you know, do as I say, not as I do.

27
00:03:50,780 --> 00:04:01,195
Both his behavior, the way he conducted himself, and the knowledge, the wisdom he had were concurrent, were accomplished.

28
00:04:01,516 --> 00:04:03,259
There was no distinction between the two.

29
00:04:03,280 --> 00:04:13,074
So his wisdom was expressed through his compassionate action, through his general demeanor.

30
00:04:15,534 --> 00:04:22,978
Whenever he went to a room, even when he was very famous, he would never just enter it.

31
00:04:23,019 --> 00:04:24,524
He'd always cough and knock.

32
00:04:26,269 --> 00:04:27,975
We've had a sort of gentility about it.

33
00:04:30,622 --> 00:04:34,487
So that's the vidyācana-sampanno.

34
00:04:34,507 --> 00:04:46,762
The sugato means that he fares well, both in his own self and in the world, as a teacher.

35
00:04:49,324 --> 00:04:56,254
It's basically a life of ease, a life of accomplishment, you might say.

36
00:04:56,954 --> 00:04:59,817
It's a similar sort of understanding.

37
00:05:01,519 --> 00:05:15,956
The loka-vidu, so he's a knower of the worlds, meaning that he discerned that there were different spheres of existence and moved within them at ease, it would seem.

38
00:05:18,220 --> 00:05:19,521
He's a knower of the worlds.

39
00:05:22,345 --> 00:05:26,649
Anuttaro purisadam masarati, he was the...

40
00:05:28,334 --> 00:05:58,172
supreme trainer of those who need to be trained sometimes tamed is used so he had some rough people who came to take his teachings and he had to be firm so as you know from your own experience there are sort of teachers who carry with them a certain authority so that when they say something you just do it

41
00:05:58,151 --> 00:06:01,274
My teacher was like that, Sadhu Janaka.

42
00:06:02,336 --> 00:06:04,338
If he said you get up at half three, you get up at half three.

43
00:06:05,139 --> 00:06:06,040
He didn't discuss it.

44
00:06:08,122 --> 00:06:09,603
He wasn't that type of person.

45
00:06:11,384 --> 00:06:18,350
And those teachers are more cajoling, more easy to bend and get them to do what you want.

46
00:06:20,192 --> 00:06:23,617
So the Buddha was very clear about the teaching.

47
00:06:23,656 --> 00:06:27,180
He was very clear about the training.

48
00:06:30,163 --> 00:06:37,197
It was once when one of the monks came to me and said, look, what is this business about the self?

49
00:06:37,718 --> 00:06:39,201
And I want these questions answered.

50
00:06:39,281 --> 00:06:40,704
Is the world infinite or not infinite?

51
00:06:40,723 --> 00:06:42,528
Does the Buddha exist or not exist?

52
00:06:42,747 --> 00:06:44,812
Does the Tāgata exist or not exist?

53
00:06:45,293 --> 00:06:48,779
I want these questions answered or I shall leave the order.

54
00:06:49,165 --> 00:06:58,218
And he said, since when did I make it a condition for you to be a member of the order that you had to have these questions answered?

55
00:07:00,401 --> 00:07:02,745
Basically, fine, you want to leave, go.

56
00:07:04,747 --> 00:07:08,213
But there was no, so he pulled him up short on that one.

57
00:07:08,233 --> 00:07:09,214
In the end, of course, he stayed.

58
00:07:12,038 --> 00:07:15,904
But he was also a satta dewa manusana.

59
00:07:15,985 --> 00:07:18,649
He was also a teacher of gods and men.

60
00:07:19,000 --> 00:07:32,060
And this refers to the skill, to his seemingly very clever skill at getting people to understand, to directly experience what he was talking about.

61
00:07:32,081 --> 00:07:34,764
I suppose the most outstanding one was of the...

62
00:07:34,745 --> 00:07:39,752
the dull monk, whose brother had actually suggested he might leave the order.

63
00:07:39,913 --> 00:07:43,218
Because in those days, of course, you had to remember the Buddha's teachings.

64
00:07:43,800 --> 00:07:49,309
And it was said that when he learnt one line of the teaching, it knocked out the line he'd just learnt.

65
00:07:49,689 --> 00:07:53,175
So he couldn't learn anything apart from that.

66
00:07:53,425 --> 00:07:55,428
When the Buddha heard this, you know, he said, no, no.

67
00:07:55,829 --> 00:08:07,696
So he gave him a very simple exercise, took a cloth, and he said, wipe your face, you know, the sweat on your face, and keep rubbing it, and just keep observing it, and keep saying, impermanent, impermanent, anicca, anicca.

68
00:08:08,237 --> 00:08:10,300
And he became fully liberated.

69
00:08:10,341 --> 00:08:13,408
It didn't work for me, but there we are.

70
00:08:15,548 --> 00:08:18,531
So he was very skillful in his teaching.

71
00:08:18,550 --> 00:08:24,396
He knew where people were at and was able to give them all sorts of little exercises.

72
00:08:25,177 --> 00:08:31,305
And that's why there's no specific technique left by him.

73
00:08:32,166 --> 00:08:42,336
So every good teacher that comes along, like the Mahasi, works on the way he spoke, what things were left, the tradition, and they come up with these techniques.

74
00:08:42,356 --> 00:08:45,419
That's why there's such a plethora of techniques.

75
00:08:45,399 --> 00:08:48,350
He didn't say one technique is good for everybody.

76
00:08:48,951 --> 00:08:53,427
That was his way of teaching, skillful means, skillful means.

77
00:08:53,447 --> 00:08:56,456
So in that sense he was an incomparable teacher.

78
00:08:58,461 --> 00:09:07,072
So buddho means here, the last two are more to do with acclamations or honorifics really.

79
00:09:07,131 --> 00:09:08,352
Buddho, the awakened one.

80
00:09:09,614 --> 00:09:13,197
It comes from the word to awake, to come out of a dream.

81
00:09:13,778 --> 00:09:17,543
So life's a dream, a bubble in a stream and all that.

82
00:09:17,964 --> 00:09:20,145
And then he's awakened, he's come out of that.

83
00:09:20,525 --> 00:09:22,849
And we often use the word enlightened for it.

84
00:09:23,926 --> 00:09:32,861
There are more adjectives in the scriptures to suggest an enlightenment, a light coming on in the dark, rather than awakening, but both are used.

85
00:09:33,143 --> 00:09:34,004
That's the buddho.

86
00:09:35,447 --> 00:09:37,850
And finally, bhagavā.

87
00:09:39,215 --> 00:09:41,379
This also refers to teacher.

88
00:09:41,880 --> 00:09:47,111
But I think here there's a certain idea of respectfulness about it.

89
00:09:47,392 --> 00:09:49,456
Because you would go to the Bhagavad.

90
00:09:49,476 --> 00:09:50,357
Where's the Bhagavad?

91
00:09:50,798 --> 00:09:53,504
So it's more to do with where is the enlightened person?

92
00:09:53,524 --> 00:09:54,927
Where's the holy one?

93
00:09:54,908 --> 00:10:13,659
whereas a noble enlightened person so that's more of a sense of someone to be venerated and those are your sort of nine basic qualities of the Buddha and although the exercises there in Theravada

94
00:10:13,639 --> 00:10:15,221
but it's never really taught.

95
00:10:16,202 --> 00:10:31,323
But it's on meditating on these qualities, meditating here in the sense of contemplating these qualities, that one gains a certain relationship to a personage of the Buddha, even though obviously it doesn't exist.

96
00:10:32,125 --> 00:10:35,809
It becomes like an image in your heart, it becomes like an image in your mind, you see.

97
00:10:36,890 --> 00:10:41,857
And the more you contemplate on what these qualities mean, it corrects your own

98
00:10:42,479 --> 00:11:12,029
image your own ideal towards which you're working it becomes quite a lovely contemplation to do in the same way you can contemplate the Dharma and the Sangha but the Buddha for in terms of developing the juice of the spiritual path the actual devotional path which brings a real joy to the heart so that's one of the exercises

99
00:11:12,567 --> 00:11:18,436
So we do metta, which is another one of those similar exercises that brings a bit of juice to the practice.

100
00:11:18,636 --> 00:11:20,679
Vipassana can be, well, heavy.

101
00:11:22,802 --> 00:11:25,027
So you've got to juice it up a bit, you see.

102
00:11:25,447 --> 00:11:34,322
So a day like on Sunday is a time when you just recollect on the teacher and the qualities of that, you know.

103
00:11:34,690 --> 00:11:36,732
And for most of them that's where we're heading.

104
00:11:36,753 --> 00:11:39,196
We're definitely heading towards the end of defilement.

105
00:11:40,077 --> 00:11:40,859
What does that mean?

106
00:11:41,940 --> 00:11:44,182
So it's a lovely exercise to do.

107
00:11:45,865 --> 00:11:48,269
Then the other two are this Pacheco Buddha.

108
00:11:48,328 --> 00:11:53,255
So here there's a private Buddha, that's how it's translated, solitary Buddha.

109
00:11:53,817 --> 00:12:04,292
And the idea is that somebody can become fully self-enlightened, so Pacheco Buddha is self-enlightened, but can't teach.

110
00:12:05,014 --> 00:12:08,019
They just can't do it, can't get it across.

111
00:12:08,921 --> 00:12:22,120
Because the two things that the Buddha did was not only to teach the Dharma, but to set up an order, an institution, which could carry the message, the Sangha, the order of monks and nuns.

112
00:12:23,602 --> 00:12:28,070
So it would seem that there are people who become fully enlightened, they just don't have those sort of qualities.

113
00:12:28,289 --> 00:12:30,312
They're not complete Sammasambuddhas.

114
00:12:31,205 --> 00:12:33,628
And then finally there's the Svākata Buddhas.

115
00:12:33,648 --> 00:12:36,110
So they're the ones who become Buddha by following a Buddha.

116
00:12:37,511 --> 00:12:47,522
So once you've devoted yourself to the Buddha's path and you become an arahat, that's the usual word they use for such a person, an arahat, then you're a Svākata Buddha.

117
00:12:49,663 --> 00:12:50,225
And you've made it.

118
00:12:50,245 --> 00:12:51,005
Then you can relax.

119
00:12:52,947 --> 00:12:56,691
Then you can really have a cup of tea.

120
00:12:56,772 --> 00:13:00,115
That's the only time you can really have a cup of tea and a cake.

121
00:13:01,528 --> 00:13:02,993
Before that, it's just indulgence.

122
00:13:03,514 --> 00:13:04,496
You're just kidding yourself.

123
00:13:07,644 --> 00:13:11,374
So I can only hope my words have been of some assistance, inspiring, shall we say.

124
00:13:12,015 --> 00:13:17,208
May you be fully liberated sooner rather than later.

